%%TITLE
Risks of nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drugs in undiagnosed intensive care unit pneumococcal pneumonia: younger and more severely affected patients.
%%ABSTRACT
The purpose of this study is to investigate whether exposure to nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) at the early stage of severe pneumococcal community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) requiring intensive care unit (ICU) admission may affect its presentation and outcome.Medical records of ICU adult patients (12-year period) with a pneumococcal CAP diagnosis were retrospectively analyzed according to previous NSAID exposure.One hundred six confirmed pneumococcal CAP were identified, 20 received NSAIDs within 4 (2-6) days before admission. Nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drug-exposed patients were younger (43.3 vs 62.2 years; P < .0001), had less frequently at least one chronic comorbid condition (40% vs 75%; P = .003), had more often complicated pleural effusions (20% vs 2.3%; P = .01), and more frequent pleuropulmonary complications (odds ratio: 5.75 [1.97-16.76]). Nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drug patients required more often noninvasive ventilatory support (25% vs 4.6%; P = .003). Intensive care unit length of stay and mortality were similar.We report as severe pneumococcal pneumonia in young and healthy patients exposed to NSAIDs as in older, more comorbid, and nonexposed ones. Nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drug use may mask initial symptoms and delay antimicrobial therapy, thus predisposing to worse outcomes.
%%METHODS
Patients
Two independent searches were performed over a 12-year period (December 1997 to 2009), one using the ICU’s electronic database, with search labels including “pneumococcal pneumonia” (Interna- tional Classiﬁcation of Diseases label J13) or “S pneumoniae” and “pneumonia” (International Classiﬁcation of Diseases labels B953 + J159/J180/J181) and the other using the Microbiology Laboratory electronic database. The 2 lists of patients were cross-checked to ensure exhaustibility and verify the ﬁnal diagnosis. Once extracted, we reviewed the complete medical records of each patient with a conﬁrmed pneumococcal CAP hospitalized in our ICU. Microbiological conﬁrmation of S pneumoniae’s responsibility for each episode relied either on the presence of at least one positive microbiological sample for S pneumoniae (blood culture or lower respiratory tract culture or the presence of S pneumoniae urinary antigen).
Exclusion criteria were the following: patients with hospital- acquired pneumonia (deﬁned as occurring 48 hours after hospital admission) whatever the causative microorganism, aspiration pneu- monia, CAP due to another causative pathogen, S pneumoniae infections other than lung, chronic usage of NSAIDs (including salicylic acid at antiinﬂammatory dosage), and important data missing (including timing of beginning of symptoms, ﬁrst medical consultation, and ﬁrst antibiotherapy).
Monitored variables
Demographic data included sex, age, smoking status, chronic alcohol intake, and working condition. Presence of comorbid condition was deﬁned as the presence of any of the following conditions for which the patient was under active medical supervision or was receiving treatment at the time of hospital admission: chronic lung disease, cardiac disease (ischemic heart disease, cardiac failure, hypertension, and atrial ﬁbrillation), cerebrovascular disease (includ- ing previous transient ischemic attacks), diabetes mellitus, chronic liver disease, chronic renal disease, active or past solid organ or hematologic malignancy, human immunodeﬁciency virus (HIV) or viral hepatitis infection, and immunosuppressive therapy such as corticosteroid or antineoplasic treatment exposure were recorded.
Time from onset of ﬁrst symptoms of pneumonia (among cough, fever, chest pain, dyspnea, and purulent sputum) to ﬁrst medical consultation and to initiation of antimicrobial treatment was recorded. Exposure to NSAID was detailed as precisely as possible for each patient, including duration of NSAID therapy before ICU admission, type of NSAIDs, nature of NSAID treatment (over the counter self-
medication or medical prescription).
All antimicrobials received before and after ICU admission were recorded.
Patient’s clinical features upon ICU admission were recorded: body temperature, heart rate, systolic and diastolic arterial pressure, respiratory rate, oxygen saturation, presence of encephalopathy,
need for vasoactive treatment, oxygen, or ventilatory support. Biological data were recorded.
All chest x-rays were independently reviewed by 2 investigators (J. M. and B. S.), blinded to the patients’ identity and NSAID exposure. The number of quadrants involved, the presence of pleural effusion or lung abscess as well as the progression of alveolar opacities or the occurrence of a new pleural effusion during ICU stay were monitored.
Speciﬁc pneumonia scores and general ICU scores were calculated: British Thoracic Society’s CURB65 score , Fine’s Pneumonia Severity Index (PSI) , Organ Dysfunction and/or Infection score , and Simpliﬁed Acute Physiology Score II (SAPS2) . We also corrected these scores excluding age and sex to decrease these factors’ weight in the measurement of severity.
Intensive care unit length of stay, status at ICU discharge, onset of organ dysfunction, need for invasive or noninvasive ventilatory support (including noninvasive mechanical ventilation or high-ﬂow nasal cannulae oxygen therapy), hemodynamic support, or renal replacement therapy were recorded.
Statistical analysis
Data were analyzed with StatView 5.0 (SAS Institute Inc, Cary, NC). Continuous variables were expressed as median (Interquartile Range), unless stated otherwise and compared using the Mann- Whitney U test. χ2 test or Fisher exact test were used to compare proportions. To identify factors associated with the occurrence of pleural and/or pulmonary complications, we selected variables by univariable analysis (P b .1) and entered them in a stepwise logistic regression analysis. A P b .05 was considered signiﬁcant.
The Institutional Review Board of the Société de Pneumologie de Langue Française approved the study. Informed consent was waived owing to its retrospective and purely observational design.
